document.masterDocTitle: Limnebius acupunctus, a new species of water beetle from Australia and Papua New Guinea (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae)

mods:titleInfo.mods:title: Limnebius acupunctus, a new species of water beetle from Australia and Papua New Guinea (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae)

subSubSection.paragraph:
Type Material.
Holotype (male): Australia , South Australia , Cudlee Creek, River Torrens,
34 ° 50 ' S
,
138 ° 49 ' E
,
15 December 2001
, C. Watts; deposited in the SAMA . Paratypes listed below.

Description. Size (length/width, mm) holotype : body (length to elytral apices) 1.04 / 0.52 , head 0.18 / 0.36 , pronotum 0.25 / 0.51 , elytra 0.60 / 0.52 . Form elongate oval, moderately convex, sides gradually arcuate, broadest near posterior angles of pronotum. Dorsum dark brown to piceous, legs and maxillary palpi slightly lighter. Head and pronotum shining, very finely very sparsely punctate. Elytral punctation slightly stronger, over ground sculpture of very weak fine microreticulation; apices conjointly truncate in both sexes, posterior angles more markedly angulate in male. Prosternum with midlongitudinal carina extended to form prominent apicomedian spine. Mesosternum with intercoxal process concave. Metasternum entirely hydrofuge pubescent, setae longer on disc than laterally. Abdomen with first five ventrites hydrofuge pubescent. Protarsomeres 1–3 slightly wider in males than females, and bearing suction setae.
Etymology. Named in reference to the needle­like tube of the aedeagus, and the size of the body.
